gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F018800/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The research examines the causes and consequences of religious transformation among marginalised ?tribal? people in central India, and looks at the connections between these changes and the ideology and practices of Hindu nationalism. It shifts the focus in studies of this latter phenomenon to recognition of the importance of religious experience in understanding the appeal of political movements in India today. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The research suggests that through a process of religious transformation, and by joining a Hindu devotional sect, people see the project of becoming ?good Hindu persons? as morally powerful and intimately bound up with strategies of protection from mystical attack. The practices that the sect promotes, and that the new devotees find so morally compelling and bodily necessary, find resonance with the message of local Hindu nationalist activists seeking to integrate ?backward tribals? into the Hindu nation. As such the research will contribute to scholarship examining the complex relationship between religiosity and politics in the world today.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>76586</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/F018800/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>020361E1-B8CA-49FD-9149-27D31D21C7A3</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Anthropology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>020361E1-B8CA-49FD-9149-27D31D21C7A3</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Anthropology</gtr:tex